{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Planting Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Below I create a code example where I plant a region containing 5% of the points and make this region anomalous. Inside of the region 80% of the points are from the red set while outside of the region 50% of the points are red. We would like to recover this planted region by using the max_halfplane scanning algorithm."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x7fdc8d286a90>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import pyscan\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import random\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_coord(i, lst):\n",
    "    return [pt[i] for pt in lst]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# l = (a, b, c) where ax + by + c = 0 => (-ax -c) / b = y\n",
    "def f(mr, x):\n",
    "        l = mr.get_coords()\n",
    "        return -(x * l[0] + l[2]) / l[1]\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_plane(red, blue, max_region, eps):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    n = np.rint(1 / eps)\n",
    "    s = np.rint(1 / (2 * eps * eps))\n",
    "    # create a region containing 5% of the points. Inside of this region points are more likely to be red. \n",
    "    #print(get_coord(1, red))\n",
    "    plt.scatter(get_coord(0, red), get_coord(1, red), marker=\".\", c=\"r\")\n",
    "    plt.scatter(get_coord(0, blue), get_coord(1, blue), marker=\".\", c=\"b\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    net = pyscan.my_sample(red, n) + pyscan.my_sample(blue, n)\n",
    "    red_s = pyscan.my_sample(red, s)\n",
    "    blue_s = pyscan.my_sample(blue, s)\n",
    "    approx_region, _ = pyscan.max_halfplane(net, red_s, blue_s, pyscan.KULLDORF)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.scatter(get_coord(0, net), get_coord(1, net), marker=\"x\", c=\"k\")\n",
    "    plt.plot([0, 1], [f(max_region, 0), f(max_region, 1)], c=\"k\", linewidth=4.0)\n",
    "    plt.plot([0, 1], [f(approx_region, 0), f(approx_region, 1)], c=\"g\", linewidth=4.0)\n",
    "    plt.xlim([0, 1])\n",
    "    plt.ylim([0, 1])\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "# generate some random points\n",
    "pts = [pyscan.WPoint(1.0, random.random(), random.random(), 1.0) for i in range(10000)]\n",
    "red, blue, max_region = pyscan.plant_halfplane(pts, .05, .5, .8)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(get_coord(0, red), get_coord(1, red), marker=\".\", c=\"r\")\n",
    "plt.scatter(get_coord(0, blue), get_coord(1, blue), marker=\".\", c=\"b\")\n",
    "plt.plot([0, 1], [f(max_region, 0), f(max_region, 1)], c=\"k\", linewidth=4.0)\n",
    "plt.xlim([0, 1])\n",
    "plt.ylim([0, 1])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The algorithms will subsample the data based on an error parameter called $\\varepsilon$. There will be two samples uses in the algorithm one of size $O(1/\\varepsilon)$ and another of size $O(1/\\varepsilon^2)$. If we do not set $\\varepsilon$ to be small enough we will not recover the region. Below I steadily decrease $\\varepsilon$ and therefore increase the sample sizes. At first we will not recover the anomalous region."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"

      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_plane(red, blue, max_region, .2)\n",
    "plot_plane(red, blue, max_region, .1)\n",
    "plot_plane(red, blue, max_region, .05)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Around .025 we get start getting very close to recovering the region and at .01 we almost perfectly recover it."
   ]
  },
